@page "/docs/components/resize-handle"

<Seo Canonical="/docs/components/resize-handle" Title="Blazorise ResizeHandle component" Description="Learn how to use the Blazorise ResizeHandle component to resize panels, sidebars, and other elements with pointer or keyboard input." />

<DocsPageTitle Path="Components/ResizeHandle" AddedVersion="Added in v2.2">
    Blazorise ResizeHandle component
</DocsPageTitle>

<DocsPageLead>
    Add an accessible drag handle to an existing panel, sidebar, or other resizable element.
</DocsPageLead>

<DocsPageParagraph>
    The <Code Tag>ResizeHandle</Code> component is a lightweight separator that resizes an element without creating or managing a pane layout.
    Place it inside the element you want to resize, or use <Code>TargetElementId</Code> when the resized element is elsewhere in the document.
</DocsPageParagraph>

<DocsPageParagraph>
    A vertical handle changes width and defaults to the end edge. A horizontal handle changes height and defaults to the bottom edge.
    Set <Code>Placement</Code> when the handle belongs on the opposite edge.
</DocsPageParagraph>

<DocsPageParagraph>
    The resize hit area is visually transparent by default, including while focused or dragging, so it does not change the attached element's appearance.
    Enable <Code>ShowGrip</Code> to render the current provider's separator surface, borders, and grip.
</DocsPageParagraph>

<DocsPageSubtitle>
    Examples
</DocsPageSubtitle>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Resizable side panel">
        Place the handle inside a relatively positioned element to resize its width. Use <Code>@@bind-Size</Code> when the application also needs the committed size.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="ResizeHandlePanelExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <ResizeHandlePanelExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Provider-styled grip">
        Enable <Code>ShowGrip</Code> to opt into a visible separator. This example also uses a horizontal handle, where dragging downward increases the panel height.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="ResizeHandleHeightExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <ResizeHandleHeightExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="External target and CSS variable">
        Set <Code>TargetElementId</Code> to resize another element. <Code>ResizeProperty</Code> can be a CSS custom property, which is useful when one value controls an element's width and related styles.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="ResizeHandleTargetExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <ResizeHandleTargetExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSection>
    <DocsPageSectionHeader Title="Resizable vertical Bar">
        A vertical <Code>Bar</Code> can expose its width through a CSS variable. Bind its <Code>Visible</Code> state and disable the resize handle while the Bar is collapsed into small mode.
    </DocsPageSectionHeader>
    <DocsPageSectionContent Code="ResizeHandleBarExample" Outlined FullWidth>
        <ResizeHandleBarExample />
    </DocsPageSectionContent>
</DocsPageSection>

<DocsPageSubtitle>
    Positioning
</DocsPageSubtitle>

<DocsPageParagraph>
    The handle is absolutely positioned, so its containing element should establish a positioning context, usually with <Code>position: relative</Code>.
    Make sure an ancestor does not clip the handle when it is placed outside the resized edge.
</DocsPageParagraph>

<DocsPageSubtitle>
    Keyboard and accessibility
</DocsPageSubtitle>

<DocsPageParagraph>
    The component renders an ARIA separator and supports arrow-key resizing. Click the handle area or reach it with the Tab key, then use the arrow keys to resize.
    Use <Code>KeyboardStep</Code> to control the keyboard increment and provide an <Code>AriaLabel</Code> that describes the resized region.
    <Code>MinSize</Code> and <Code>MaxSize</Code> apply to both pointer and keyboard interaction.
</DocsPageParagraph>

